WEBVTT

00:02.480 --> 00:03.959
(Alarm)

00:09.680 --> 00:11.636
Morning, Dad.

00:13.840 --> 00:16.114
Don't be a bad daddy. Smile!

00:17.480 --> 00:19.436
Come on! (Laughs)

00:21.000 --> 00:27.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

00:57.680 --> 00:59.636
The crowd is hushed.

01:00.520 --> 01:02.476
Thank you!

01:31.520 --> 01:33.351
Sorry l'm late.

01:33.440 --> 01:35.396
Meeting ran on.

01:36.200 --> 01:38.236
So, what's for dinner?

01:38.320 --> 01:40.276
- Chinese.
- Oh, great!

01:41.320 --> 01:43.276
- Where is it?
- At the takeaway.

01:44.280 --> 01:47.238
- Will you go?
- We had takeaway last night.

01:47.320 --> 01:49.117
Yeah, but that was lndian.

01:49.200 --> 01:51.998
What are you planning for the Sunday roast -
a kebab?

01:52.080 --> 01:55.993
David, don't start. This has got to be in
by tomorrow and editing takes time.

01:56.080 --> 01:58.389
Surely you just press spellcheck?

02:00.200 --> 02:04.557
How difficult can children's books be?
They're less than ten words to a page.

02:04.640 --> 02:07.359
Precisely!
So each one has to be chosen carefully.

02:09.160 --> 02:13.153
- ls this the last night you're going to work late?
- lf you let me get on with it.

02:15.080 --> 02:17.514
- And tomorrow we won't have takeaway?
- No.

02:18.920 --> 02:20.990
You can take me out for dinner instead.

02:23.160 --> 02:26.038
- And did he?
- He wanted to but l had to work late.

02:26.120 --> 02:28.076
- l thought you said that...
- l know.

02:28.160 --> 02:31.436
But since l've been back at work
it takes twice as long to do things.

02:31.520 --> 02:34.876
l've lost my confidence, can't make decisions.
lt's a bloody nightmare.

02:34.960 --> 02:37.349
- lt's being married to David.
WOMAN: Tea or coffee?

02:37.440 --> 02:39.510
Oh, um... What are you having?

02:40.680 --> 02:41.715
Karen!

02:41.800 --> 02:43.995
Tea, please. Yeah, l'll have tea.

02:44.080 --> 02:47.550
You were good at your job before you had Josh.
Why not now?

02:47.640 --> 02:50.552
<i>- l wish my boss had your faith.
- l wish you did.</i>

02:50.640 --> 02:52.756
Take for both and we'll eat in.

02:52.840 --> 02:55.991
- Make mine a takeaway.
- We're supposed to be having lunch together.

02:56.080 --> 02:59.789
We've queued together. Sorry, Rachel,
but l've got to get back to the office.

02:59.880 --> 03:01.393
You stay.

03:01.480 --> 03:04.597
And look like l've no mates,
or that l'm some slapper on the pull?

03:04.680 --> 03:06.636
You never know. You might get lucky!

03:07.520 --> 03:09.192
Bye.

03:17.120 --> 03:19.076
Look at them all.

03:19.240 --> 03:21.196
Doesn't it make you want to vomit?

03:22.760 --> 03:24.716
He does.

03:25.120 --> 03:27.475
People like that give evolution a bad name.

03:28.880 --> 03:30.836
They're the ''missing link''.

03:33.920 --> 03:35.876
(Sings) Heaven knows l'm miserable now.

03:35.960 --> 03:39.714
- What's up with you?
- l just thought there'd be more to it than this.

03:41.560 --> 03:44.358
When you were younger, Pete,
didn't you have dreams?

03:44.440 --> 03:46.476
- Yeah.
- Well, like what?

03:46.560 --> 03:49.916
One, l seem to remember,
involved Samantha Fox at a jumble sale.

03:50.000 --> 03:52.833
Not like that. l mean dreams. Ambitions.

03:54.360 --> 03:57.716
Um, no. Not unless you count
Samantha Fox at the jumble sale.

03:59.480 --> 04:01.675
l was going to be a world leader.

04:01.760 --> 04:03.671
Well, that's certainly ambitious.

04:04.400 --> 04:07.278
The closest l ever came
was captain of the Under 1 2s.

04:08.360 --> 04:11.955
We can't all be world leaders.
Some of us have to be sheep.

04:12.040 --> 04:14.190
Sitting at t'baaas! Baaas!

04:15.240 --> 04:17.310
l woke up this morning and realised...

04:19.399 --> 04:21.356
..this is it.

04:22.760 --> 04:24.716
lt was a good side, the Under 1 2s.

04:25.480 --> 04:27.152
Life is elsewhere.

04:27.920 --> 04:30.559
And l don't have...the address.

04:32.800 --> 04:36.759
What you need is a sense of purpose.
l'm just the man to give it to you. So...

04:36.840 --> 04:40.355
- How do you fancy being Adam's godfather?
- Oh, l'd love to.

04:40.440 --> 04:43.193
Take your time to think about it.
lt is a responsibility.

04:43.280 --> 04:45.430
No, it's not. ls it?

04:45.520 --> 04:48.273
- You have to remember his birthday.
- Rachel can do that.

04:48.360 --> 04:50.351
- Set him a good example.
- Rachel can do that.

04:50.440 --> 04:53.876
- Be someone he can turn to.
- When he can't talk to his parents?

04:53.960 --> 04:58.112
Listen, little Adam, you're probably not gay,
but if you are...it's fine.

04:59.840 --> 05:03.355
- Maybe this is a bad idea.
- Go on, go on. l can be trusted.

05:03.440 --> 05:05.078
All right. Um...

05:05.160 --> 05:07.515
Be someone to tell him about life.

05:07.600 --> 05:09.477
Oh, well, sure.

05:09.560 --> 05:10.879
Life's elsewhere.

05:10.960 --> 05:13.394
(Mimics him) And you don't have the address.

05:14.200 --> 05:15.713
You tosser.

05:19.880 --> 05:21.632
l've got the focus group results.

05:21.720 --> 05:23.676
How does Millie score?

05:23.760 --> 05:26.035
Quite well. Stanley The Sports Car does better.

05:26.120 --> 05:28.315
Stanley? But he's the villain of the piece.

05:28.400 --> 05:31.995
Mm-hm. But kids love it
when he belches exhaust fumes in Millie's face.

05:32.080 --> 05:34.036
- (Mutters) God.
- Karen?

05:34.120 --> 05:36.076
- Yeah?
- Could l have a word?

05:37.320 --> 05:41.108
lf she wants Stanley
to have his own series...l'm leaving.

05:44.600 --> 05:46.158
<i>AIexander WeIcht.</i>

05:49.560 --> 05:52.870
- Booker Prize winner?
- Yeah. Blanket Of Tears. Beautiful book.

05:52.960 --> 05:55.155
Never knew sex could be so good.

05:55.240 --> 05:57.708
That scene where she's ironing...

05:57.800 --> 05:59.950
We're going to publish Alec's new novel.

06:00.040 --> 06:01.758
Mmmm!

06:01.840 --> 06:03.796
(Saucy laughter)

06:05.560 --> 06:07.516
l want you to be his editor.

06:08.800 --> 06:11.598
- Me.
- Mm. Alec insists on the best.

06:12.360 --> 06:15.875
- Me?
- You've always had the perfect eye for detail.

06:17.960 --> 06:21.077
l gave you children's books
when you came back just to ease you in.

06:21.160 --> 06:25.039
- lt's time you spread your wings.
- Well, l'm not actually sure l'm up to it, Gina.

06:25.120 --> 06:27.236
Let me be the judge of that, OK?

06:27.320 --> 06:29.276
Well, l have commitments, you see.

06:30.040 --> 06:31.678
Your son?

06:31.760 --> 06:35.833
- l was actually thinking more my husband.
- l'm sure David will understand.

06:37.360 --> 06:39.954
- lt's a wonderful opportunity.
- l know.

06:40.040 --> 06:43.191
- That anybody in their right mind would jump at.
- l know.

06:43.280 --> 06:46.113
So why do l think you're about to turn it down?

06:47.480 --> 06:51.359
Good news, love.
Sheila's agreed to be godmother.

06:51.440 --> 06:54.637
- Do you think that's a good idea?
- Oh... (Splutters)

06:54.720 --> 06:56.915
- What's wrong with her?
- She's a Christian.

06:57.000 --> 06:59.833
And she is my only sister.

07:00.600 --> 07:03.876
And she hasn't got any children of her own,
and...

07:03.960 --> 07:05.916
And, and, and, and...

07:06.000 --> 07:07.911
And, and, and, and what, love?

07:08.000 --> 07:11.037
And your mum rang.
They want to come and visit this weekend.

07:11.120 --> 07:13.315
- l hope you said we were away.
- We're not.

07:13.400 --> 07:14.389
So?

07:15.600 --> 07:18.319
Oh, for God's sake.
They're Adam's grandparents.

07:18.400 --> 07:20.595
lt's nice they want to see him.

07:20.680 --> 07:22.591
lt's lovely.

07:22.680 --> 07:24.272
l think.

07:24.360 --> 07:26.635
- They'll only be staying a week.
- A week!

07:26.720 --> 07:28.676
(Whimpers) To ten days...

07:30.400 --> 07:33.676
- Thank you, David.
- l'm a godfather. To my niece. Rebecca.

07:34.560 --> 07:36.630
Oh, yeah? How old is she?

07:36.720 --> 07:38.676
Oh, let's see.

07:38.760 --> 07:41.718
When she was born
l was working on the Lanskey takeover,

07:41.800 --> 07:43.836
which means she must be er...

07:44.680 --> 07:46.636
- She's six.
- Six?

07:49.120 --> 07:53.318
- ls it that long since Lanskey's went under?
(Doorbell)

07:55.240 --> 07:57.196
David's close to his niece, is he?

07:57.280 --> 07:59.350
l'm surprised he remembered her name.

08:04.560 --> 08:07.757
- Oh, hi. Karen Morrison lives here, yeah?
- Yes.

08:07.840 --> 08:10.115
l'm Alec Welcht.

08:10.200 --> 08:11.679
Her author.

08:11.760 --> 08:13.796
Oh, yes! Millie The Mountain Bike.

08:13.880 --> 08:16.838
- Yes. l didn't realise it had an author.
- Millie...?

08:16.920 --> 08:19.480
Tell me, how do you fill in the rest of your time?

08:19.560 --> 08:22.597
Well, children's books can be literature too,
you know.

08:22.680 --> 08:24.033
Mm!

08:24.920 --> 08:26.797
- Yeah, come in.
- Thanks.

08:26.880 --> 08:29.155
Karen? lt's your ''author'' to see you.

08:29.880 --> 08:32.792
- Sorry, l didn't catch the name.
- Alexander Welcht.

08:35.799 --> 08:37.916
- Karen.
- Mr Welcht.

08:38.000 --> 08:41.150
- Nice to meet you.
- Like the real writer. Do you ever get confused?

08:41.240 --> 08:43.595
- Well, l am now. Hello, good evening.
- Hi.

08:43.679 --> 08:45.318
- Hello.
- Very nice to meet you.

08:45.400 --> 08:47.550
<i>Er, David, this is Alexander Welcht.</i>

08:51.520 --> 08:53.875
Oh, l'm so sorry, Mr Welcht. l'm so sorry.

08:53.960 --> 08:57.191
- Please. Call me Alec.
- Alec. l am so sorry. l had no idea.

08:57.280 --> 08:59.077
l didn't mean to belittle...

08:59.160 --> 09:02.311
Children's books, they're really...
lf l'd known it was you...

09:02.400 --> 09:04.914
- lt's OK.
- Tell me what you think of this wine.

09:05.000 --> 09:06.956
- Please, sit down.
- Oh, thanks.

09:07.040 --> 09:09.315
- Something to eat?
- Humble fare, but...

09:09.400 --> 09:11.834
lt smells delicious, but l don't have time.

09:13.240 --> 09:15.117
- So, Alec, you're a writer.
- Yeah.

09:15.200 --> 09:20.513
- Anything we would have heard of?
- Adam! Mr Welcht wrote Blanket Of Tears.

09:20.600 --> 09:22.033
ADAM: Oh, right!

09:22.120 --> 09:23.951
- You read it?
- No, l saw the movie.

09:24.040 --> 09:25.473
Ah.

09:25.560 --> 09:28.120
Yeah. Hope the book was better!

09:28.200 --> 09:30.156
Well, the Booker judges thought so.

09:33.040 --> 09:35.508
- l started writing a novel once.
- Oh, God...

09:35.600 --> 09:37.556
- Did you finish it?
- No, it was shite.

09:37.640 --> 09:41.872
Should have stuck with it. First draft's
always shite. That's why you need a good editor.

09:41.960 --> 09:47.159
That's why l'm here. l just found out today
the editor l'd requested has turned me down.

09:47.240 --> 09:49.117
(Sighs and tuts) He must be mad.

09:49.200 --> 09:51.270
Either that or she's very discerning.

09:51.360 --> 09:53.191
l wanted to find out which.

09:56.640 --> 09:58.278
Karen!

09:59.000 --> 10:02.231
Er...Mr Welcht, it would really be an honour
to work with you,

10:02.320 --> 10:04.390
but l don't have the time to do it justice.

10:04.480 --> 10:06.869
- Of course you do.
- How would you know?

10:08.560 --> 10:11.358
We have a nanny. We eat takeaway food.

10:11.440 --> 10:13.635
- Not all the time?
- You hate takeaway food.

10:13.720 --> 10:15.915
- l could grow to like it.
- Or cook.

10:19.440 --> 10:23.433
Alec, Karen would be delighted
to be your editor.

10:24.360 --> 10:25.634
Would you?

10:27.040 --> 10:29.110
Yes, l would...Alec.

10:29.880 --> 10:34.317
Well, that...that's just brilliant.
l thought l was going to have to beg.

10:35.600 --> 10:39.275
l hate to drink and run,
but l've got some people to meet for dinner.

10:41.200 --> 10:43.350
Hope you can edit as well as you can cook.

10:44.080 --> 10:45.752
See you tomorrow, Karen.

10:46.680 --> 10:49.752
Good night, everyone. Sorry to barge in.
l'll see myself out.

10:49.840 --> 10:51.558
No, no, let me.

10:52.280 --> 10:55.716
- No-one ever compliments my cooking.
- God, l loved Blanket Of Tears.

10:55.800 --> 10:57.756
God, it was so sexy.

10:58.520 --> 11:00.875
- Do you remember the bit where she...?
- lroning.

11:00.960 --> 11:02.837
l read it with one hand.

11:02.920 --> 11:05.150
(Raunchy laughter)

11:09.400 --> 11:11.356
- Adam?
(Clattering)

11:14.240 --> 11:17.869
- Adam, what are you doing?
- l knew it was up there somewhere.

11:17.960 --> 11:20.599
l couldn't sleep, not after meeting Alec Welcht.

11:20.680 --> 11:22.830
l know he has that effect on women, but...

11:22.920 --> 11:26.595
He's fired me, Rach. He's given me
the sense of purpose l was lacking.

11:26.680 --> 11:30.116
- My novel. l'm going to finish it.
- At three o'clock in the morning?

11:30.200 --> 11:33.670
- Hemingway didn't work office hours.
- No, and he died alone.

11:35.440 --> 11:38.830
- Don't you want to read it?
- l'll wait till it's in paperback.

11:41.240 --> 11:41.990
Ha!

11:42.920 --> 11:44.876
l knew that was a good title.

11:50.360 --> 11:52.316
(Moans softly)

11:53.360 --> 11:55.237
(Gasps)

12:02.240 --> 12:04.310
Oh, David...

12:05.200 --> 12:07.156
Oh, David...

12:08.600 --> 12:11.558
- Karen, l'm trying to read here.
- Oh, so read later.

12:13.240 --> 12:15.196
l will. lt's a long article.

12:24.840 --> 12:26.796
(Door bangs shut)

12:27.720 --> 12:29.551
(Baby cries)

12:29.640 --> 12:31.756
Oh, for heaven's sake. Karen!

12:33.640 --> 12:35.551
(Reads) Night.

12:35.640 --> 12:37.596
Winter.

12:37.840 --> 12:39.796
Dark.

12:39.960 --> 12:41.678
Cold.

12:41.760 --> 12:44.513
- (Stifled giggle)
- The howl of a dog...

12:45.560 --> 12:47.551
..an anthem of despair.

12:49.400 --> 12:51.356
A distant sound.

12:52.120 --> 12:54.076
Growing louder.

12:54.880 --> 12:57.440
- Choo...
- (Laughs openly)

12:57.520 --> 12:59.476
..choo...

13:01.280 --> 13:03.236
- ..choo.
- (Laughs)

13:04.560 --> 13:07.916
- lt might sound better in the morning.
- l doubt it!

13:08.000 --> 13:09.956
Pumping pistons.

13:10.920 --> 13:12.876
- Rattling rails.
- (Laughs)

13:13.800 --> 13:15.313
lron horse?

13:16.120 --> 13:18.076
(Sobs with laughter)

13:19.840 --> 13:22.070
- Go on.
- l thought you were trying to sleep.

13:22.160 --> 13:24.116
What, and miss this?

13:32.080 --> 13:35.231
- l think l'll start from scratch.
- Oh, Adam!

13:38.560 --> 13:40.516
(Sounds horn)

13:49.600 --> 13:51.192
Hooray!

13:52.320 --> 13:53.753
They're here.

13:53.840 --> 13:58.356
JENNY: lf it starts getting to you,
take a deep breath, count to a hundred.

13:59.200 --> 14:00.997
(Takes a deep breath)

14:01.080 --> 14:06.234
One, two, three, four, five, six, seven...

14:06.320 --> 14:08.276
(Baby grizzles)

14:08.360 --> 14:10.476
l brought some provisions.

14:11.360 --> 14:13.271
We do have shops in Manchester.

14:14.000 --> 14:15.718
We like certain brands.

14:15.800 --> 14:19.110
- Aah!
- There. Hello!

14:19.200 --> 14:22.510
- How was your journey?
- A lot of traffic on the A34.

14:22.600 --> 14:26.070
A34? What's wrong with the M6?
lt's much quicker.

14:26.160 --> 14:28.628
- Since when?
- Since they built it. Look at this.

14:28.720 --> 14:32.190
- What about the roadworks at Knutsford?
- Come off at Sandbach.

14:32.280 --> 14:36.034
- And get caught up in Holmes Chapel?
- Well, it's better than Wilmslow.

14:36.120 --> 14:39.430
- lt wasn't bad. Took us two hours.
- l could knock a half hour off that.

14:39.520 --> 14:41.238
- Oh, yes?
- Yes.

14:41.880 --> 14:43.916
Milk.

14:44.000 --> 14:46.434
One, two, three...

14:46.520 --> 14:50.035
Karen! Karen,
have you seen the papers l left on the table?

14:50.160 --> 14:52.435
- No.
- You were in the bathroom a long time.

14:52.520 --> 14:54.829
l was finishing Alex's book.

14:54.920 --> 14:56.478
Oh, yeah? Any good?

14:56.560 --> 14:58.755
Well, the climax doesn't disappoint.

14:58.840 --> 15:00.637
Ramona!

15:00.720 --> 15:02.676
Charles. Hi, it's David.

15:02.760 --> 15:05.069
Sorry l missed you on Spotlight Northwest.

15:05.160 --> 15:07.435
Yeah, we had a few friends round to dinner.

15:07.520 --> 15:09.590
You've heard of Alexander Welcht?

15:09.680 --> 15:11.557
The author, yeah.

15:11.640 --> 15:14.598
No, seriously. He's a terribly nice guy. Yeah.

15:14.680 --> 15:16.636
OK, see you at 1 1 :00. Jolly good. Bye.

15:16.720 --> 15:17.755
Ramona!

15:17.840 --> 15:20.718
- What did you think of the meal last night?
- What?

15:21.440 --> 15:24.830
- Can you remember what it was?
- l haven't got time for quizzes.

15:24.920 --> 15:26.478
- Ramona!
- Coming!

15:26.560 --> 15:28.676
Ramona, have you seen... What is she doing?

15:28.760 --> 15:31.274
- l thought they were rubbish.
- They are now.

15:31.360 --> 15:33.032
Hey, well done, Ramona.

15:33.120 --> 15:34.792
She used the past tense.

15:34.880 --> 15:38.156
- Haven't you a job to go to?
- Alex is coming here this morning.

15:38.240 --> 15:41.516
- l hope you're going to get dressed.
- Of course l am.

15:41.600 --> 15:45.479
- He's taking me to lunch.
- Oh, the punishing world of publishing.

15:47.560 --> 15:49.516
Say hi to Alec for me.

15:51.520 --> 15:54.193
Karen,
you didn't complain that l haven't kissed you.

15:54.280 --> 15:56.236
l didn't have to, David.

15:57.320 --> 15:59.276
You remembered.

16:06.160 --> 16:08.310
Oh. The christening's a week on Sunday.

16:08.400 --> 16:11.358
- What do l have to do?
- Well, just turn up. Look pious.

16:12.080 --> 16:15.356
You can practise.
And we'd like you to read something for Adam.

16:15.440 --> 16:18.113
- What?
- Anything you like.

16:18.200 --> 16:20.156
Jen's sister's reading the Bible.

16:20.960 --> 16:22.791
- All of it?
- Course not.

16:23.960 --> 16:26.235
Oh, God, l hope not. Better check.

16:28.320 --> 16:30.117
l might write something.

16:30.200 --> 16:34.591
- Oh. How is ''the novel'' coming along?
- lt's a painful process.

16:34.680 --> 16:37.114
- Writer's cramp?
- Writer's block.

16:37.200 --> 16:39.634
- This is my ideas book.
- l see.

16:39.720 --> 16:43.679
l thought l'd write from experience
and then l realised...l haven't had any.

16:43.760 --> 16:46.115
Mm. You should talk to my dad.

16:47.000 --> 16:49.753
War hero. Bootlegger. Romeo.

16:49.840 --> 16:53.071
- l thought he was a florist.
- Oh, he is. And a bullshitter.

16:53.960 --> 16:58.476
(Over vacuum cleaner) So there l am
giving Frank Sinatra a leg-up over this wall...

16:58.560 --> 17:00.835
- Chorlton-cum-Hardy.
- He was doing a concert.

17:00.920 --> 17:04.151
Yeah. ln Chorlton-cum-Hardy.

17:05.280 --> 17:08.670
- ln Manchester, at the Palace!
- He was very good.

17:09.640 --> 17:12.915
- So you saw him, then?
- No, we couldn't get tickets.

17:13.000 --> 17:14.797
But the papers liked him.

17:14.880 --> 17:16.632
Audrey!

17:16.720 --> 17:18.675
You don't need to do that.

17:18.760 --> 17:20.557
Just trying to be helpful.

17:21.280 --> 17:22.838
Feet!

17:27.280 --> 17:31.353
So, Dad, there you are
giving Frank Sinatra a leg-up over this wall.

17:31.440 --> 17:35.433
You would've thought
he'd have slipped you a couple of spare tickets.

17:35.520 --> 17:38.273
Look, do you want to hear this story?

17:38.360 --> 17:42.035
- He might have been telling the truth.
