Listen, you will come tonight?

35:24.080 --> 35:27.595
- l'm going to finish the book.
- Fine, just don't finish it tonight.

35:27.680 --> 35:29.830
Have dinner tonight. Please.

35:29.920 --> 35:32.275
Are you really that concerned
about me and Pete?

35:32.360 --> 35:36.114
Mm...no. No, you'll be all right.
You'll patch it up. You always do.

35:36.200 --> 35:41.274
No, it's bloody Wallace and Gromit - Pete's
parents. l could just do with the moral support.

35:44.560 --> 35:46.312
OK, we'll come.

35:46.400 --> 35:48.152
Hoorah.

35:49.960 --> 35:51.916
Only because it's you.

35:58.680 --> 36:00.671
You and Pete have had a falling out, eh?

36:03.320 --> 36:05.276
l'm not supposed to mention it.

36:07.600 --> 36:10.751
- Thanks, Pete.
- Reminds me of when you were kids.

36:10.840 --> 36:12.796
They were always bickering.

36:13.520 --> 36:15.476
Then Pete would sit on him.

36:16.640 --> 36:18.790
Some things haven't changed, then.

36:18.880 --> 36:20.836
Got your notebook, have you?

36:32.520 --> 36:36.752
- Audrey, why don't you go and sit down?
- l'll just finish these plates.

36:36.840 --> 36:39.479
But we haven't even used them yet.

36:40.360 --> 36:42.316
They gather dust in the cupboard.

36:43.160 --> 36:45.879
Oh. Do you like your carrots that thin?

36:45.960 --> 36:47.951
Audrey, sit down!

36:48.040 --> 36:51.476
- You could cut the atmosphere in there with a...
- (Whimpers)

36:55.720 --> 36:57.711
Do you need a hand?

36:57.800 --> 36:59.233
(Gasps)

36:59.320 --> 37:01.151
DAD: l hear you're Adam's godfather.

37:01.240 --> 37:04.869
- Unless l've been sacked.
- Come on, Adam. Pete wouldn't do that.

37:06.200 --> 37:08.156
- Jenny won't let me.
- Hm.

37:08.240 --> 37:10.879
And what do you think
of the young fella's name?

37:10.960 --> 37:12.518
Adam?

37:12.600 --> 37:14.033
l like it.

37:14.120 --> 37:16.076
Adam Preston Gifford.

37:17.280 --> 37:19.475
- No room for Algernon.
- No.

37:19.560 --> 37:22.791
Nor Sigismund, or Egbert, or Beowulf.

37:22.880 --> 37:25.348
Algernon's been in the family for generations.

37:25.440 --> 37:29.069
My great-grandfather was an Algernon
and every Gifford since.

37:29.160 --> 37:33.199
- lt's Pete's middle name.
- And they never let me forget it at school.

37:33.280 --> 37:34.872
What's wrong with Algernon?

37:34.960 --> 37:39.795
lt's ugly, it's old-fashioned,
and in its shortened form it means pond scum!

37:39.880 --> 37:42.348
- That was his nickname.
- lt's our heritage!

37:43.080 --> 37:45.640
- Do you want to destroy that?
- Apparently.

37:45.720 --> 37:48.712
'Ey, we could add it after Preston.

37:49.680 --> 37:51.875
- Yeah!
- No. No way.

37:51.960 --> 37:53.712
One daft name's enough.

37:53.800 --> 37:58.078
Besides, he's not having four initials.
People will think he's upper class.

38:02.680 --> 38:05.240
Then you won't see us at the christening.

38:21.880 --> 38:25.111
- (Ramona sobs) ..l say to him.
KAREN: l don't want to know!

38:25.200 --> 38:27.156
(Ramona sobs hysterically)

38:27.960 --> 38:31.111
- l'm not bloody interested, Ramona.
- But it's not true!

38:31.200 --> 38:34.317
l don't care, Ramona!
You should have thought of that before!

38:34.400 --> 38:36.675
But l ask him to help...

38:36.760 --> 38:38.113
David!

38:38.840 --> 38:40.478
(Sobs)

38:40.560 --> 38:43.870
- Have you told her to pay for her phone calls?
- l fired her.

38:43.960 --> 38:45.075
Why?

38:46.760 --> 38:48.716
Because she's having an affair.

38:49.840 --> 38:51.876
She wouldn't be the first, would she?

38:52.920 --> 38:55.957
You shit! You never read my note, David!

38:57.240 --> 39:01.995
- How long have you been shagging Ramona?
- l haven't. lt was our first...or rather, it wasn't.

39:02.080 --> 39:04.389
Look, Ramona's got a crush on me, right?

39:04.480 --> 39:08.519
And l, well...l thought l'd take advantage,
since you've been shagging Alec Welcht.

39:08.600 --> 39:12.229
- What?
- Don't deny it, Karen. Adam told me everything.

39:12.320 --> 39:14.470
Adam? Your source was Adam?

39:14.560 --> 39:17.154
Who got it from Rachel.
Who presumably got it from you.

39:17.240 --> 39:19.196
David, l never slept with Alec.

39:19.960 --> 39:24.954
l won't pretend it didn't cross my mind - that's
what l told Rachel - but it never happened.

39:26.280 --> 39:28.236
l think he prefers younger women.

39:29.280 --> 39:31.236
l see.

39:31.320 --> 39:34.551
- But you thought about it, didn't you?
- Yes, l did, David.

39:36.320 --> 39:39.039
He paid me attention. He flattered me.

39:39.120 --> 39:40.678
l can flatter you.

39:45.120 --> 39:47.236
You've got a great throwing arm.

39:52.320 --> 39:56.279
l'd hoped Pete would inherit his father's looks,
not his temperament.

39:57.640 --> 40:00.029
Audrey, um...

40:02.040 --> 40:04.838
Really sorry...l held a knife on you.

40:04.920 --> 40:06.672
That's all right, dear.

40:07.680 --> 40:10.319
You've always been a little bit excitable.

40:14.800 --> 40:17.712
Pete's really upset
that you won't be at the christening.

40:17.800 --> 40:19.836
- Oh, we will.
- Eh?

40:19.920 --> 40:23.799
When Pete wants one thing
and you want another, who wins?

40:25.800 --> 40:27.472
Moi!

40:28.800 --> 40:31.758
They say men marry their mothers.

40:32.760 --> 40:34.512
Oh, no. (Laughs)

40:34.600 --> 40:36.113
Bye, love.

40:36.840 --> 40:38.319
See you, Mum.

40:38.400 --> 40:40.356
- Bye-bye, love.
- Bye.

40:40.440 --> 40:42.317
- Look after my grandson.
- Yeah.

40:43.040 --> 40:44.996
And my son.

40:48.240 --> 40:50.196
JENNY: Bye.

40:52.840 --> 40:54.558
- Pete.
- Yeah?

40:54.640 --> 40:56.596
Which way to the A34?

40:58.160 --> 40:59.673
A34?

41:01.400 --> 41:03.038
Right.

41:04.840 --> 41:06.796
Obstinate sod!

41:06.880 --> 41:08.836
Don't you turn left for the A34?

41:16.760 --> 41:18.716
- Oh, dear.
- Oh, that's awful.

41:18.800 --> 41:20.756
Awful.

41:20.840 --> 41:23.070
- l should have listened to you.
- Mm.

41:23.160 --> 41:25.469
- l shouldn't have said anything to Adam.
- No.

41:25.560 --> 41:27.278
l'm sorry.

41:28.280 --> 41:32.114
- How did you get Ramona to stay on?
- An apology and a pay rise.

41:33.360 --> 41:35.555
You should get Adam to contribute.

41:35.640 --> 41:38.313
Oh, l'm not the vindictive kind, Rachel.

41:39.520 --> 41:41.476
- Hi, girls.
- Adam.

41:43.840 --> 41:45.796
Have you finished it already?

41:46.520 --> 41:48.476
Well, there were no long words.

41:48.560 --> 41:50.516
Karen, l want you to be brutal.

41:50.600 --> 41:54.036
l know we're friends,
but l value your professional opinion.

41:54.120 --> 41:56.076
What can l say, Adam? lt left me...

41:56.840 --> 41:58.558
Speechless.

41:59.280 --> 42:02.352
lt reminds me of what
Truman Capote said of Jack Kerouac.

42:02.440 --> 42:04.078
- Really?
- Mm.

42:04.160 --> 42:06.799
''This isn't writing, it's typing.''

42:08.080 --> 42:10.548
ln your case, it's not even good typing.

42:11.520 --> 42:14.398
Um...when l said ''brutal'', um...

42:14.480 --> 42:18.029
There's a simile in chapter five l quite liked,
though it's not original.

42:18.120 --> 42:20.554
The rest is just wastepaper.

42:25.000 --> 42:28.197
l um...think l'll...get myself a drink.

42:28.400 --> 42:30.595
Best make it a double, eh?

42:30.680 --> 42:32.398
l haven't finished yet.

42:35.600 --> 42:37.556
(Organ music)

42:46.600 --> 42:48.511
Quickly.

42:48.600 --> 42:50.556
All right, all right. Careful.

42:52.360 --> 42:54.316
- Hi.
- Sorry we're late.

42:54.400 --> 42:56.356
- Hi.
- Hi.

42:57.360 --> 42:59.237
For you.

42:59.320 --> 43:01.880
We're accepting gifts after the christening.

43:01.960 --> 43:03.757
lt's my novel.

43:05.720 --> 43:08.359
l decided friendship
was more important than fame.

43:10.760 --> 43:12.671
Denis Law?

43:15.480 --> 43:17.198
Anyway, Karen said it was shite.

43:18.280 --> 43:20.748
ls there any sign of your parents yet?

43:20.840 --> 43:22.353
No.

43:22.440 --> 43:24.715
They'll be here. Your mum promised.

43:24.800 --> 43:26.756
You might want to move inside now?

43:38.520 --> 43:41.318
l'm Sheila. Jenny's sister.

43:41.400 --> 43:43.868
- The Christian?
- Of course.

43:43.960 --> 43:46.076
As godfather, aren't you?

43:47.600 --> 43:49.795
- Have you got him a present?
- A Bible.

43:51.400 --> 43:53.436
Oh, you haven't as well?

43:54.480 --> 43:56.550
l was this close to, but...no.

43:57.280 --> 43:59.350
l got him a Peter Rabbit bowl and mug.

44:03.960 --> 44:05.916
lt's Wedgwood.

44:06.840 --> 44:08.796
Hiya. ls David not with you?

44:08.880 --> 44:11.235
No, he's on the phone. Some deal with Tokyo.

44:12.080 --> 44:14.036
Are we the last?

44:14.120 --> 44:15.838
Possibly.

44:17.960 --> 44:21.919
Hai. Watashiwa Tokyoe ikimasu...

44:24.520 --> 44:26.431
Er, next week.

44:26.520 --> 44:28.715
You don't speak Japanese, do you?

44:28.800 --> 44:30.756
Yes. As a matter of fact, l do.

44:32.800 --> 44:36.236
Perfect. Could you tell him
l'm going to be in Tokyo next week?

44:36.960 --> 44:38.712
Moshi moshi. Odenwa kaerimashita.

44:38.800 --> 44:41.439
SHElLA:
And if your hand causes you to sin,

44:42.800 --> 44:44.392
cut it off.

44:44.480 --> 44:46.869
lt is better for you to enter life maimed

44:46.960 --> 44:50.794
than with two hands
to go to hell to the unquenchable fire.

44:51.880 --> 44:54.917
And if your eye causes you to sin,

44:55.880 --> 44:57.472
pluck it out.

44:58.440 --> 45:02.194
lt is better for you to enter
the kingdom of God with one eye

45:03.000 --> 45:05.753
than with two eyes to be thrown into hell.

45:10.440 --> 45:15.195
We're now going to hear from Adam's
godfather and namesake Adam Williams.

45:16.560 --> 45:18.312
Brilliant.

45:19.760 --> 45:21.716
- Arigato.
- Doo itashimashite.

45:23.840 --> 45:26.035
ADAM: l'm quite nervous, actually.

45:27.680 --> 45:29.636
A lot of eyes looking at me.

45:30.440 --> 45:34.228
Um...no-one's ever asked me
to be a godfather before.

45:35.440 --> 45:37.396
l can't see why not.

45:38.400 --> 45:42.678
And so l'm especially proud
that my best friends have.

45:45.120 --> 45:47.953
l've got some notes here somewhere.

45:50.680 --> 45:53.797
When a baby's born er...everything changes.

45:55.080 --> 45:57.036
Families change.

45:57.680 --> 45:59.716
Everyone else moves up a generation.

46:00.760 --> 46:03.877
Pete...who is a son...

46:03.960 --> 46:05.951
(Mobile rings)
- ..is now also a father.

46:09.080 --> 46:10.593
Yeah?

46:10.680 --> 46:12.636
Hai. Hai.

46:12.720 --> 46:14.676
Er... (Snaps fingers)

46:16.640 --> 46:18.710
Um... Where was l? Er...

46:18.800 --> 46:20.756
Oh, yeah, fathers and sons.

46:21.800 --> 46:27.113
l asked Pete's dad - Algy -
what it had been like for him to be a father.

46:27.200 --> 46:28.918
This is going to be good.

46:29.000 --> 46:31.070
And er...he sent me this.

46:36.680 --> 46:41.196
''lnevitably parents love their children
more than their children love them.

46:43.440 --> 46:47.592
A father looks at a son and sees part of himself.

46:48.960 --> 46:51.793
They say, 'Be careful what you wish for.'

46:52.600 --> 46:57.993
My wish for my son was that he grew up
independent of mind and strong of will.

46:59.040 --> 47:01.190
That he has drives me mad.

47:02.600 --> 47:04.556
lt also fills me with pride.''

47:04.640 --> 47:07.108
Yeah? Well, why didn't the old git turn up, then?

47:07.200 --> 47:09.998
''l know that Pete will be a good father.

47:11.320 --> 47:13.276
l've seen the way he looks at his son -

47:14.840 --> 47:16.796
with love.

47:17.800 --> 47:24.592
A love that only a father can recognise, and
which l recognise, cos that's how l look at Pete.

47:25.360 --> 47:28.079
(Mobile rings)
ADAM: Oh, for God's sake!

47:28.160 --> 47:30.720
You shouldn't blaspheme in church.

47:30.800 --> 47:33.075
And you shouldn't heckle.

47:33.160 --> 47:34.912
Hello?

47:38.480 --> 47:40.232
OK, Mum.

47:42.680 --> 47:44.636
What is it, Pete?

47:45.720 --> 47:47.472
My dad.

47:47.560 --> 47:49.516
He's dead.

48:09.840 --> 48:11.796
lronic, really.

48:12.600 --> 48:14.556
Your father never went to church.

48:16.080 --> 48:18.435
Then he has a heart attack
on his way to one.

48:20.600 --> 48:22.556
l'm going to be a good dad to him.

48:24.160 --> 48:26.116
l wanted to be to you.

48:30.120 --> 48:32.076
He never knew how much l loved him.

48:32.560 --> 48:34.516
Yes, he did.

48:35.880 --> 48:38.394
You just had a funny way of showing it, love.

48:38.480 --> 48:40.311
- Look after my grandson.
- Yeah.

48:41.040 --> 48:42.996
And my son.

48:47.520 --> 48:49.476
You're just like him.

48:50.800 --> 48:52.552
Come on.

